or the amount of

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.740
heat that's required
in order to have a

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:00.940
chemical reaction go.

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:05.250
And we'd established so far two
ways to think about how we

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:08.510
can measure what the overall
enthalpy of a reaction is.

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:11.250
And I just wanted to introduced
one more technique

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:13.920
that we can use to do that.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.240
And this relies on the fact
that when we talk about

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:19.470
enthalpy or we talk about the
heat change of a reaction,

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:22.540
this is a state function, and
any time we're talking about

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:25.410
state function, it's independent
of path.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.850
So essentially, all that we're
worried about is the state

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:29.770
that we started in.

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:32.790
So, for example, when we were
talking about the oxidation of

00:08:32.790 --> 00:08:36.680
glucose, the state that we start
in are the reactants, so

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:38.650
it's glucose plus oxygen.

00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:41.540
And what we ended up with were
six moles each of carbon

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:43.320
dioxide and water.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:46.180
So, we don't care how we get
there in terms of making this

00:08:46.180 --> 00:08:48.660
calculation, all we're
interested in is the

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:51.930
difference between those two
states, to think about the

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:55.660
overall change in enthalpy.

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:58.200
So, for example, when we talked
about how we could

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:01.180
calculate this, one way that we
can do it, and we'll look

00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:04.800
at these numbers even more
specifically in a second, is

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:07.630
thinking about instead of going
straight down here,

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.180
which we might not have the
numbers available to us to

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:13.030
calculate directly, we can think
about well, what happens

00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:16.760
if instead we break apart this
glucose molecule and decompose

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:19.500
it into its elements, because
using tables in the back of

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:22.670
our book, for example, we can
figure out what the change in

00:09:22.670 --> 00:09:26.070
enthalpy is of this
reaction here.

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:28.470
That doesn't quite get us to
where we need to go though, so

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:31.920
then we can think about the
enthalpy of formation of six

00:09:31.920 --> 00:09:34.180
carbon dioxide molecules.

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:37.410
And then we can go one step
further and think about the

00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:40.590
enthalpy of formation for
six water molecules.

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:43.250
So this is just a round
about way of going

00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:44.570
from here to here.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:47.680
Instead we went up and then
down and then down, but

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:50.130
because it's a state function,
we're absolutely

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:52.290
allowed to do this.

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:54.680
And to formalize this, we can
talk about what's called

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:56.960
Hess's law.

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:01.230
And Hess's law just tell us that
if we have two or three

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:04.560
or any number of chemical
reactions that we can add

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.330
together in order to get the
chemical equation that we're

00:10:07.330 --> 00:10:10.950
actually interested in, we can
figure out the change in

00:10:10.950 --> 00:10:14.230
enthalpy of that reaction that
we're interested in, just by

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:18.250
adding together all of the other
enthalpies of reaction

00:10:18.250 --> 00:10:20.780
for every other reaction that
we had to add together in

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:21.730
order to get there.

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:26.460
So, let's take a look at what
we're talking about here.

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:29.260
So when I just showed you that
example graphically, I'm just

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.470
writing it out more like an
equation here, because the

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:34.260
nice thing about Hess's law,
is it allows you to think

00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:37.520
about chemical reactions kind
of as if they're algebraic

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:38.530
expressions.

00:10:38.530 --> 00:10:41.560
So we can just add all of these
different expressions

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:43.690
together, and if we're thinking
about algebra, we can

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:45.690
just think about crossing things
out that are in the

00:10:45.690 --> 00:10:48.220
reactants versus in
the products.

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:51.220
So if we do this, what we end
up getting is the reaction

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:54.560
that we're interested in, the
oxidation of glucose to form

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:56.940
carbon dioxide in water.

00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:59.930
So let's look pretty carefully
at exactly the fact that these

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:02.930
all cancel out to give us the
reaction I say we get.

00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:05.940
So, for example, we can think
about the oxygen molecules --

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:10.110
we can cancel out 6 here and 6
here, as long as we multiply

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.540
this whole reaction by 6.

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:16.790
Again, we can get rid of those
last 3 oxygen molecules there.

00:11:16.790 --> 00:11:19.650
Similarly, we can cross out
our 6 hydrogens from the

00:11:19.650 --> 00:11:23.590
products with 6 molecular
hydrogens from the reactants.

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:27.860
And then the last thing we can
cancel out are our carbon

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:30.550
atoms -- we have 6 in the
products, and we have 6 in the

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:32.030
reactants here.

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:34.570
So you'll see that the only
things that are not canceled

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:37.770
out is what's left in
our bottom reaction.

00:11:37.770 --> 00:11:41.150
So we can go ahead and just add
up all of these different

00:11:41.150 --> 00:11:42.710
reaction enthalpies.

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:45.380
In the first case what we're
going to have is an enthalpy

00:11:45.380 --> 00:11:47.240
