an overall reaction, what

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:13.770
we want to do is take the
sum of all of those bond

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:20.990
enthalpies of our bonds that are
broken, and what we want

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:26.050
to do is subtract from that
the sum of all our bond

00:14:26.050 --> 00:14:29.870
enthalpies of our bonds
that are formed.

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:37.190
All right, so let's think a
little bit more about what

00:14:37.190 --> 00:14:38.240
this means.

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:41.050
So, if we're talking about bonds
broken, are we talking

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:42.510
about reactants or products?

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:44.190
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:44.370
PROFESSOR: .

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:44.620
Reactants.

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:47.560
So, essentially we're summing
up the bond enthalpy of

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:51.210
reactants and subtracting
it from the products.

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:54.620
All right, great.

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:57.040
So that's our first
strategy there.

00:14:57.040 --> 00:15:01.450
The second strategy that we
learned is thinking about bond

00:15:01.450 --> 00:15:06.400
enthalpies of reaction by using
the enthalpy change in

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:08.200
terms of the enthalpy
of formation.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:12.450
So this one is sometimes a
little bit more intuitive,

00:15:12.450 --> 00:15:15.160
because we're talking about the
enthalpy change it takes

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:17.770
in order to form a
given molecule.

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:20.250
So, if we're trying to do a
calculation using enthalpies

00:15:20.250 --> 00:15:24.860
of formation, what we find is
that delta h of the reaction

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:30.750
is equal to the sum of the
delta h of formation of

00:15:30.750 --> 00:15:31.640
products or reactants?

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:32.930
STUDENT: Products.

00:15:32.930 --> 00:15:36.580
PROFESSOR: Products, good.

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:42.440
Of products minus the delta h of
formation, and this is the

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:45.310
sum again of reactants.

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:51.900
All right, and our third
strategy is what we just

00:15:51.900 --> 00:15:55.120
talked about, which is Hess's
law, and in fact, both one and

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:59.080
two are applications of Hess's
law -- specific applications,

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:01.830
but any application of Hess's
law you can use any way of

00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:04.760
adding up different equations
to get the final enthalpy of

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:06.450
the reaction.

00:16:06.450 --> 00:16:09.270
The reason I wanted to put these
two strategies, however,

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:11.880
on the board right next to each
other, is so we can just

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:14.310
confront a point of confusion
that happens a lot with

00:16:14.310 --> 00:16:17.230
students, which is why in the
first case do we have

00:16:17.230 --> 00:16:20.510
reactants minus product, and
in the second case we have

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:22.690
products minus reactants.

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:25.190
So, you need to keep these two
straight when you're doing

00:16:25.190 --> 00:16:28.490
your calculations in terms of
enthalpies, and the reason is

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:31.500
because the definition of a
bond enthalpy when we're

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:35.240
talking about bonds, is the
enthalpy that it takes in

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:38.230
order to break the bond, the
amount of heat that goes in to

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:39.560
breaking a bond.

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:42.240
So it's typically a positive
number, because if you have a

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:44.500
stable bond you have to
put heat into it in

00:16:44.500 --> 00:16:45.660
order to break it.

00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:48.920
So you end up having a positive
bond enthalpy here.

00:16:48.920 --> 00:16:51.390
In contrast, when we're talking
about enthalpies of

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:54.720
formation, now we're talking
about is the change of

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:57.360
enthalpy in order to
form a molecule.

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:00.710
So, for example, if we have a
nice stable molecule with

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:04.240
strong bonds in it, what we're
going to find is that the

00:17:04.240 --> 00:17:08.990
delta h of formation, would that
be positive or negative?

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:10.190
So it's negative.

00:17:10.190 --> 00:17:13.770
So you'd end up with a negative
delta h of formation.

00:17:13.770 --> 00:17:16.410
So because you're talking about
a term that's negative

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.650
here where it would be positive
in the first case,

00:17:19.650 --> 00:17:22.050
you end up flipping signs
to have it work out.

